<font color="#FF0000">WAR AND RACISM</font><br>
<tt>Thu Dec 12 22:54:47 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
When I first learned of The Wall, I was very moved by it's design.  I had seen too many war monuments glorifying war &quot;heroes&quot; with statues.  One of the things which impressed me most during my 12 months in Vietnam was that there were no &quot;heroes&quot; - we were all just people depending upon and looking out for each other, because we knew that no one else was going to do it for us.  We were just trying to stay alive long enough to serve our time so that we could come back home.  Most of us didn't want to be there; a lot of us weren't fortunate enough to come home; a lot of us came home deeply scared - physically and emotionally.<br><br>
Maya Lin, I truly respect you for your courage and integrity to fight for your beliefs inspite the controversy and deceit surrounding the shock of discovery that the designer of the The Wall was not only a student, but a woman of Asian descent.  Your designs have provided us with the beginnings of a dialog with which to explore the pain and feelings of loss that come from war, instead of glorifying it.  When I finally got up the courage to visit The Wall, it was an incredibly powerful experience. <br>
 <br>
So I want to thank you, Maya Lin, on behalf of all people, both living and dead, the Americans, Vietnamese, Laotians, Cambodians, Austrailians, Thai, Korean, all of us, for your sensitivity and ability to touch this place within us all through your visual vocabulary by creating a stark visual reminder that war is about death and loss and grieving, which doesn't end merely because the killing stops.  We each carry the scars of the experience with us as individuals and as cultures for many, many years.  And it is only through the grieving process that we can truly come to understand our common bonds of humanity and transend the racism and begin to heal ourselves.
<p><code>-- robb@sprynet.com  (Robb Sauerhoff) </code><p>


